  <section class="faq-section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header"><span class="section-tag">FAQs</span><h2>Frequently Asked Questions About Large Cap Funds</h2></div>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>What is the difference between large cap fund and index fund?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>Large cap funds are actively managed — a fund manager selects stocks from the top 100 companies aiming to outperform the benchmark (Nifty 50/Sensex). Index funds passively replicate the benchmark by holding the same stocks in the same proportion. Active funds have higher expense ratios (0.5%–1%) but aim for better returns, while index funds have lower costs (0.1%–0.3%) and match market returns. In recent years, many active large cap funds have struggled to consistently beat index funds, making Nifty 50 index funds an increasingly popular choice.</p></div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>How much should I invest in large cap funds?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>Financial advisors recommend allocating 50%–70% of your equity portfolio to large cap funds, with the rest in mid/small caps for growth. For a balanced overall portfolio, equity allocation itself depends on age (100 minus age is a common rule). A 30-year-old might allocate 70% to equity (with 50% in large caps = 35% of total portfolio). Start with ₹5,000–₹10,000 SIP and increase annually.</p></div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>Can large cap funds give negative returns?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>Yes, in the short term. Large cap funds can deliver negative returns during market downturns — they fell 25%–35% during the 2020 COVID crash. However, historically, no 7-year period in Indian equity markets has delivered negative returns. If you stay invested for 5+ years, the probability of positive returns is over 95%. This is why a long-term horizon is essential for equity investing.</p></div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>Should I choose direct or regular plan?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>Direct plans have lower expense ratios (by 0.5%–1%) since they don't include distributor commissions. Over 20 years, this difference can result in 10%–15% more wealth. If you can research and select funds yourself, always choose direct plans. If you need a financial advisor's help, regular plans include their commission but you benefit from professional guidance.</p></div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>When should I switch from large cap to other funds?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>You don't need to switch — rather, diversify. Once comfortable with equity investing (after 1–2 years), add mid cap and small cap funds to your portfolio for higher growth potential. Maintain large cap as your core holding. Consider switching individual funds only if they consistently underperform their benchmark and peers over 3+ years, not based on short-term returns.</p></div></div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

